default3.12
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere are no national standards in collision investigation; the ACPO road death investigation manual is advisory 
defaulto
defaultnly and 
defaultnor is there any monitoring of consistency or procedures used by the 43 different police services across the country.  
defaultMany police investigations fall well below the level of acceptable competence (Jake Thompson, Eilidh Cairns, Marie Vescoe) result
defaulting in little chance of prosecution or prevention of further similar deaths through corrective action
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultRECOMMENDATION: A national minimum good practice standard agreed by ACPO and others including the national charity for collision investigators (ITAI).  
defaultThis should include prompt dealing with witnesses and the use of the Self Administered Questionnaire that allows witnesses to record information immediately.
default&#xa0;
default3.13
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA review of the court outcomes for drivers prosecuted for killing or seriously injuring cyclists in London found that between 2007 and 2010 of the 50 fatal cyclist collisions considered only half were taken to court. Of those 25 prosecutions only 12 were c
defaultonvicted of death by dangerous or careless driving. Law breaking committed with vehicles is treated much more leniently than with other dangerous machinery, or other crime committed on the street. Prosecutors do not receive specialized training and they ra
defaultrely visit the crash site or attend any inquest. 
default&#xa0;
defaultRECOMMENDATION: Greater accountability and transparency during the investigation process including reporting of all police forces on the number of cases put forward to the CPS for prosecution 
defaultand the numbe
defaultr of cases not put forward and the reasons why
default not
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultRECOMMENDATION: Greater accountability and transparency during the prosecution process including a requirement for prosecutors to consider visiting the scene and 
defaultfor 
defaultthe publication of 
defaultthe 
defaultnumber of cases which are deemed not suitable 
defaultfor prosecution and the reasons why
default not
default.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default3.14
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is a lack of transparency with the charging decision in road crashes, especially by the police in injury collisions, and the number of drivers in crashes that ha
defaultve broken the law is not counted.
default Therefore t
defaulthe victim of a road crash is not counted in crime statistics so the number of people killed or injured by law breaking drivers is not recorded or monitored at all at present. We do not know the number of innocen
defaultt victims injured by Dangerous Driving, Careless Driving, or Drink-Driving, as these charges do not mention when an injury has resulted. 
default&#xa0;
defaultRECOMMENDATION: Vi
defaultctims of law breaking drivers to be included in victim of crime statistics.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default3.15
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCollision investigators are often asked in court what could be done to prevent these deaths. Their answers are unusually ill-informed and without due consideration. Coroners have powers make recommendations to prevent further similar deaths. These are ofte
defaultn not excersized because coroners are unaware of preventative low cost measures. In the case of Judicial Review into the inquest of Eilidh Cairns the coroner argued that ‘there were no practicable, preventative measures’ which could have been implemented
default t
defaulto prevent death
default. This is simply untrue.
default&#xa0;
defaultRECOMMENDATION: M
defaultandatory and regular training and monitoring of collision investigators, prosecutors and coroners so they can consistently explain the full circumstances of the death and propose preventative 
defaultmeasures to reduce future road deaths.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default3.16
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEvent Date Recorders (EDRs) or ‘Black Boxes’ are a simple, cheap and increasingly available technology, which can dramatically reverse the escalating problem of road death and long-term disability.  Black boxes are 
defaultused to improve safety by monitoring the manner in which vehicles are being driven by recording distance driven, start and end time, average speed and time above speed limit, acceleration and deceleration and the highest speed for each trip. Information ca
defaultn be used for driver training and supervision through provision of continuous records, and for crash reconstruction and prevention through detailed vehicle data just before and after a crash. They can also incorporate automatic crash notification (e-call) 
defaultusing GPS to alert the police and emergency services detailing location and potential severity. Drivers driving for work cause the majority of vulnerable road user deaths. 
default&#xa0;
default3.17
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA report by the Institution of Mechanical Engineers
default 
default‘Intelligent Transport Intell
defaultigent Society’ published in March 2012 calls for vehicles to be installed with collision-avoidance technologies, which could help eliminate cyclist and pedestrian deaths caused by driver ‘blind-spots’, and state that they should be made mandatory for al
defaultl U
defaultK buses and lorries by 2015
default&#xa0;
defaultRECOMMENDATION:
default L
defaultegislation to require and regulate 
defaultcollision avoidance technologies
default with all devices meeting minimum technological standards 
defaultfor all high risk groups including 
defaultyoung or novice drivers, all public sector agencie
defaults, all commercial drivers including public transport vehicles, company cars, and all construction vehicles accessing public roads.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultC. Whether it would be desirable and feasible to segregate cyclists from other road users, including, for example, by prohibiting HGVs from entering city centres at peak hours.default&#xa0;
